{"id": 232016180, "title": "SIMMONS: It was All About Bob in Game 1 of Stanley Cup Final", "text": "So many of the Oilers players think they were a break or two away, a shot here, a save there, about winning Game 1. Maybe they were. But to begin with, you can\u2019t win if you don\u2019t score. Florida scored the winning goal on the first shot of Game 1, not that Skinner had any chance to stop Carter Verhaeghe\u2019s winning goal. But it wasn\u2019t lost in victory that Verhaeghe scored the big goal because, like McDavid and like Draisaitl, that\u2019s what he does at playoff time. \u201cThe driver of it was Sergei,\u201d said Panthers coach Paul Maurice. And his goalie was fantastic, stopping 32 Edmonton shots, most of that in the first two periods. The Panthers aren\u2019t a pretty hockey team. That\u2019s not what makes them special. They rarely lose battles for loose pucks on the boards. They dump pucks in. They chase. They win forecheck battles. This is old fashioned hockey at a time when old fashioned isn\u2019t all that favourable anymore.", "summary": "SUNRISE, Fla. &#8212; The first scar of the Stanley Cup Final belongs to Connor McDavid. In a way, the trace of blood above his chin and below his lip was almost symbolic &#8212; he didn\u2019t look at all like the winner he is after the 3-0 defeat in Game 1 of the Cup Final. He [&#8230;]", "url": "https://torontosun.com/sports/hockey/nhl/simmons-it-was-all-about-bob-in-game-1-of-stanley-cup-final", "image": "https://smartcdn.gprod.postmedia.digital/torontosun/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Stanley-Cup-2024-06-09.jpg?quality=100&strip=all", "video": "", "publish_date": "2024-06-09 14:18:24", "author": "Steve Simmons", "authors": ["Steve Simmons"], "language": "en", "source_country": "ca", "sentiment": -0.189}